866	2024-07-16	11:56:00	Email In	Hi Lexi, for reference, here's the email that my ex-fiance sent. \r\n\r\n---------- Forwarded message ---------\r\nFrom: Nic DiChiara <ndichiara10@gmail.com>\r\nDate: Mon, Jul 15, 2024 at 9:57 AM\r\nSubject: Re: Transfer House Ownership\r\nTo: Sarah Pham <sarahpham9999@gmail.com>\r\n\r\n\r\nMrs. Tuckerman, \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNearly every point you claimed in your previous email is factually incorrect, and I would advise you to read this message very carefully and re-evaluate your approach.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe mortgage payoff amount is not $520k. It’s actually $506k — a substantial $14k difference. \r\nThe phone number you shared for the attorney is not her number. That’s actually the phone number for our previous lender, United Wholesale Mortgage. \r\nI didn’t “decide to not pay the mortgage”. We agreed to terms and conditions in writing via SMS, where you stated “my parents are planning on buying the house in cash, so don’t worry about paying the mortgage” and “If everything is done before the upcoming mortgage payment, then you don’t need to pay the November mortgage”. Given these communications, our MOU, your advance buyout payment, and the fact that I upheld my end of the written terms and conditions we agreed to, taking me to court over this would be a frivolous exercise that would serve no purpose other than costing you additional legal expenses just to embarrass yourself before the court.\r\nThere’s no such thing as “pressing charges” in a civil case. That term only applies to criminal cases and your attempt to use it to scare and pressure me is disgusting and utterly laughable. I will not be intimidated with legal action by someone that does not even know the basic vocabulary. \r\nThe 8 month time duration you’re attempting to hold over my head was determined by your own actions, not mine, and therefore is completely inadmissible. You and your family asked me in writing to allow you time to sell your other property, and I complied with that request. Again, this would be dismissed in court so fast your head would spin. \r\n\r\n\r\nI would recommend that you think long and hard about threatening legal action against me because we can both play that game. In the State of Georgia, a Promise to Marry is Legally Enforceable. See Kelley v. Cooper, where the appeals court upheld that the terminating party (you) can be held liable for expenses incurred by the non-terminating party based on the promise to marry. In our case, given your termination of our engagement and the evidence that I have Mrs. Tuckerman, I have an extremely strong case to take you to court over every penny I put into that house, the ring, my move out expenses, legal expenses, the mental anguish, and more. You would be wise to avoid that — the law is established and the evidence is undoubtedly on my side.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMy attorneys have advised me that if we cannot work out the house topic together and it does go to court, the Judge will immediately order it to go to third-party mediation, and that will cost both of us more than would make sense with margins this tight. In the worst case of us not being able to come to an agreement, the Judge will order it to be sold, and that will most likely not be at a price either of us like. Neither of us should want that and it’s in both of our best interest to talk this out 1:1 and negotiate this together. So, let’s set aside the legal threats and hostility and just work this out here. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nGiven all of this, I propose 2 options: \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIF you want to own the house, I will agree to sign over my half ownership, as long as I am compensated for the equity growth UP UNTIL I ceased mortgage payments. In November, via SMS, we both agreed that the AVM valuation at that time of $565k was acceptable by us both. That would mean that the house appreciated $25k and thus I am entitled to $12.5k in equity growth. In addition, I will also need to collect the $2,511.48 for the fixtures that remained with the house that you agreed to pay for but never did. The total buyout amount I would agree to is the advance you’ve previously paid, plus the $15,011.48 described above.\r\nIF you do not want to own the house, then we must list it for sale immediately. An option that has presented itself is that a friend of mine, Matt, is a real estate agent here in Atlanta and has generously offered to list our house at 0% commission. Yes, he is a personal friend, but he is also a professional and I would trust him 100% to do this fairly and properly for both of us. This would mean substantial savings in closing costs, and would help ensure that we both end up in the green on this deal. If we go this route, I would even be amenable to capping my proceeds from the sale to no more than the total buyout amount that was described above, thus avoiding the need to litigate the sale proceeds any further. You would keep all the rest. \r\n\r\n\r\nI’ve presented here two reasonable and fair solutions. Let me know your thoughts. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n-Nic DiChiara\r\n\r\n\r\nOn Thu, Jul 11, 2024 at 7:39 PM Sarah Pham <sarahpham9999@gmail.com> wrote:\r\nHi Nic,\r\nI have been talking to Amber about next steps for listing the property. These are the numbers we discussed:\r\n\r\n$520k - House pay off amount\r\n$2000 - Closing costs\r\n5% brokerage commission fee\r\n$574,900 - Listing price\r\n\r\nTotal Profit: $24,155 - Capital gains tax (because we did not live in the property for over 2 years)\r\n\r\nAmber has suggested that you call her if you have any questions on these numbers. The listing price was determined by the houses in our area that have sold and are currently being sold. There is a house exactly like ours that is a little old, but doesn't have a steep driveway and is being sold for ~$580k and has been on the market for over 50 days now. \r\n\r\nRegarding your first suggestion on getting an appraisal done - \r\nIf we get an appraisal done, our appraisal won't hold up on the buyer. This is because the buyer will have their own loan, and that lender will have their own appraisal done, they will not use the one we have done. We could put the house up for sale at the appraisal price, but that doesn't mean the buyer will buy it at that price. Having it appraised does not mean anything, it's the price that it's going to sell for that matters. \r\n\r\nRegarding your second suggestion on hiring a third party real estate attorney -\r\nAmber has recommended a fair attorney, her name is Amy Davis (855-753-6201). Amy gave some legal advice and said that since you are legally financially responsible for the home, you cannot decide not to pay the mortgage for 8 months and still collect equity. I am owed half of the mortgage back for the months you have not been paying.\r\n\r\nAmy's suggestion was that it seems you have already won because you were given $15k from me and haven't been making mortgage payments for 8 months. She says the best route for you is to sign a Quitsclaim deed and walk away with the $15k. \r\n\r\nI will outline the options for you:\r\n1. You don't sign Quitsclaim deed. In a perfect scenario, we gain around $20k in profit, split that in half and minus the $15k I already gave you, you would be in the negatives and would have to reimburse me. Then we would both sit with an attorney that handles litigations. I will also bring the matter of what you owe me for 8 months of payment to court. \r\n\r\n2. You sign the Quitsclaim deed, you walk away with $15k that I gave you back in November 2023 and I will not press charges and let go of the 8 month payment that's due. \r\n\r\nLet me know which route you want to take, I need this done by July 19, 2024. If not, then my lawyer will be reaching out to you.\r\n\r\n- Sarah Pham	349	9
